The Kubernetes Crusade: Workshop on Defending & Attacking Kubernetes

Lab: Deploy basic application using Helm

Continue Using The Same Terminal

Let’s install nginx using a pre-packaged Helm Chart on the local Kubernetes cluster.

  • Search the Helm repository for packages related to NGINX.

There are no repo currently, let's add helm chart.

helm search repo nginx

  • Add the stable & bitnami repository to Helm. The stable & bitnami repository contains a large number of pre-configured Helm charts for popular applications.
helm repo add stable https://charts.helm.sh/stable
helm repo add bitnami https://charts.bitnami.com/bitnami

The bitnami/nginx chart is maintained by Bitnami, a company that specializes in creating secure and easy-to-use application packages.

  • Update the local Helm repository cache with the latest information.
helm repo update

  • Searche the Helm repository for NGINX package, after the repository has been updated.
helm search repo nginx

  • Installs the nginx package from the bitnami/nginx.
helm install nginx bitnami/nginx

  • Verify the nginx installation by running kubectl.
kubectl get all

  • Run the helm list command to list down the deployed or failed releases.
helm list

  • Port forward the newly create nginx service.

It is likely that the NGINX deployment that you have installed using Helm is listening on port 8080, but you have forwarded it to port 80 on your local machine using the kubectl port-forward command.

Run echo $(curl -s ifconfig.me:80) on the terminal to get ipv4 and access via browser. Or use the domain name as mentioned below.

kubectl port-forward service/nginx 80:80 --address 0.0.0.0

  • Access the nginx application via public endpoint http://<subdomain>.securitydojo.co.in by visitng the browser.

In case want to exit, Type ctrl+c to close the port-forward.

  • Cleanup: To uninstall the nginx helm package.
helm uninstall nginx
